04401nam a22006615i 9780271086866DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20212020pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710868667 a10.1515/97802710868662doi  a(DE-B1597)584550  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aRA644.R3bN33 2020 7aSOC0570002bisacsh04a636.089/695309542231 aNadal, Deborah, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRabies in the Streets :bInterspecies Camaraderie in Urban India /cDeborah Nadal. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2020  a1 online resource (278 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAnimalibus: Of Animals and Cultures ;v1600tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tList of Abbreviations -- tIntroduction: Viral Connections -- t1 Humans -- t2 Food in the Middle -- t3 Dogs -- t4 Macaques -- t5 Cows -- t6 Living with Rabies -- tConclusion: Interspecies Camaraderie -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFound in two-thirds of the world, rabies is a devastating infectious disease with a 99.9 percent case-fatality rate and no cure once clinical signs appear. Rabies in the Streets tells the compelling story of the relationship between people, street animals, and rabies in India, where one-third of human rabies deaths occur. Deborah Nadal makes the case that only a One Health approach of "interspecies camaraderie" can save people and animals from the horrors of rabies and almost certain death.Grounded in multispecies ethnography, this book leads the reader through the streets and slums of Delhi and Jaipur, where people and animals, such as dogs, cows, and macaques, interact intimately and sometimes violently. Nadal explores the intricate web of factors that bring humans and animals into contact with one another within these urban spaces and create favorable pathways for the transmission of the rabies virus across species. This book shows how rabies is endemic in India for reasons that are as much social, cultural, and political as they are biological, ranging from inadequate sanitation to religious customs, from vaccine shortages to reliance on traditional medicine.The continuous emergence (and reemergence) of infectious diseases despite technical medical progress is a growing concern of our times and clearly questions the way we think of animal and environmental health. This original account of rabies challenges conventional approaches of separation and extermination, arguing instead that a One Health approach is our best chance at fostering mutual survival in a world increasingly overpopulated by humans, animals, and deadly pathogens.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aHuman-animal relationshipszIndia. 0aRabies in animalszIndia. 0aRabieszIndia. 0aUrban animalszIndia. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Disease & Health Issues.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311074521440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271086866zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271086866423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271086866.jpg  a978-3-11-074521-4  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK